# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-devops
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps is available in two different forms: on-premises ("Server") and online ("Services").
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The latter form is called Azure DevOps Services (formerly Visual Studio Online before it was renamed to Visual Studio Team Services in 2015).
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The cloud service is backed by the Microsoft Azure cloud platform.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] It uses the same code as the on-premises version of Azure DevOps, with minor modifications, and implements the most recent features.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] A user signs in using a Microsoft account to set up an environment, creating projects and adding team members.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] New features developed in short development cycles are added to the cloud version first.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] These features migrate to the on-premises version as updates, at approximately three-month intervals.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps is built on multi-tier scalable architecture.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The primary structure consists of an application tier responsible for processing logic and maintaining the web application portal (referred to as Team Web Access or TWA).
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps is built using Windows Communication Foundation web services.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] To support scalability, the application tier can be load balanced and the data tier can be clustered.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The primary container is the project collection.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] A project collection is a database that contains a group of Team Projects.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Data from the project collection databases is aggregated into the warehouse database, which denormalizes the data in preparation for loading into an Analysis Services cube.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The warehouse and the cube allow complex trend reporting and data analysis.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps can integrate with an existing SharePoint farm.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] To support teams requiring enterprise project scheduling, Azure DevOps also integrates with Microsoft Project Server.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Microsoft provides two standalone redistributed APIs for connecting to Azure DevOps: a Java SDK and a .NET Framework SDK.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] These APIs allow for client connectivity to Azure DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Because Azure DevOps is written on a service-oriented architecture, it can communicate with virtually any tool that can call a web service.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Another extensible mechanism is subscribing to system alerts: for example, alerts that a work item was changed, or a build completed.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] When used in an extensible scenario, these alerts can be sent to a web service, triggering actions to alter or update work items (such as implementing advanced business rules or generating work items programmatically based on a given scenario).
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The data warehouse can also be extended through the creation of custom data warehouse adapters.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps supports Visual Studio 2010 and later, Microsoft Test Manager (MTM) 2012, and 2013.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Eclipse, older versions of Visual Studio, and other environments can be plugged into Azure DevOps using the Microsoft Source Code Control Integration Provider.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Microsoft Excel and Microsoft Project are also supported to help manage work items which allows for bulk update, bulk entry and bulk export of work items.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Microsoft Project can be used to schedule work when conforming to a waterfall software development methodology.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Both Excel and Project support bi-directional updates of data.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] This allows, for example, project managers to put a schedule in Project, have that work imported into Azure DevOps where developers update the work and then the schedule can be updated.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] With Team Foundation Server 2012, Microsoft PowerPoint was also integrated with Azure DevOps to enable rapid storyboard development to help with the requirements management process.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The integration provides extensible storyboard shapes that can be used to build any type of interface mockup that can then be animated with PowerPoint's built-in functions.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] These storyboards can then be linked to work items.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] In an effort to handle the growing geographic dispersion of teams and to involve stakeholders earlier and more often in the process, Microsoft added the Feedback Client.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] This tool allows users to exercise an application, annotate what they are seeing with audio and video, capture screens and provide contextual feedback to the development team.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] At the heart of Azure DevOps is the "work item", which can be work that needs to be accomplished, a risk to track, a test case, a bug, etc.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Work items are defined through the XML documents and are highly extensible.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Work items are combined into a **Process Template** that contains these and other pieces of information to provide a development framework.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps includes Process Templates for the Microsoft Solutions Framework for Agile, Scrum and CMMI.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Work items can be linked to each other using different relationships to create a hierarchical tree of work items or a flat relationship between work items.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Work items can also be linked to external artifacts such as web pages, documents, source code, build results, test results and specific versions of items in source control.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The flexibility in the work item system allows Azure DevOps to play many roles from requirements management to bug tracking, risk and issue tracking, as well as recording the results of reviews.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The extensible linking capabilities ensure that traceability from requirements to source code to test cases and results can be accomplished and reported on for auditing purposes as well as historical understanding of changes.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps supports two different types of source control – its original source control engine called Team Foundation Version Control (TFVC) and with the release of TFS 2013, it supports Git as a core source control repository.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] TFVC is a centralized version control system allowing teams to store any type of artifact within its repository.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] TFVC supports two different types of workspaces when working with client tools – Server Workspaces and Local Workspaces.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Server workspaces allow developers to lock files for check-out and provide notification to other developers that files are being edited.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] A frequent complaint for this model is that files on the development machine are marked as read-only.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] It also requires developers to "go offline" when the server can't be contacted.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Local workspaces were designed to avoid these problems.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] In a local workspace scenario files are not read-only and they do not have to be checked out before working on them.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] As long as the files are on the developer's local machine, it doesn't matter if the server is connected or not.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Conflicts are dealt with at check-in time.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] To improve performance for remote clients, Azure DevOps includes the ability to install Proxy Servers.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Proxy servers allow source control contents to be cached at a site closer to the developers to avoid long network trips and the associated latency.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Check-ins are still performed directly against the Azure DevOps application tier so the Proxy Server is most beneficial in read scenarios.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] As part of the source control engine, Azure DevOps supports a number of features to help developers ensure the code that is checked in follows configurable rules.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Azure DevOps also supports a Code Analysis feature that when used independently is known as FxCop.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] With the release of TFS 2013, Microsoft added native support for Git.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] This is not a Microsoft specific implementation but a standard implementation based on the libgit2 library.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Because Microsoft took the approach of using a standard library, any Git client can now be used natively with Azure DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] This allows tools on any platform and any IDE that support Git to connect to Azure DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] In addition, if developers do not want to use Microsoft's Team Explorer Everywhere plug-in for Eclipse, they can choose to use eGit to connect to Azure DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The reporting infrastructure consists of a data warehouse, which is a relational database and a SQL Server Analysis Services data cube.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Both of these sources are available for reporting through SQL Server Reporting Services when this option is installed.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Since these are standard database and cube structures, any tool which can point to these data sources can report from them.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] This includes tools such as Cognos, Tableau, Excel and other reporting tools.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Included with each out of the box process template is a set of reports for reporting services which cover Build information, Test results and progress, project management, agile reports (Backlog Overview, Release Burndown, Sprint Burndown and Velocity), bug and issue data.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] New reports can be created using Report Builder for SSRS and any of the existing reports can be modified.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] TFS 2013 introduced a new feature called "light-weight reporting" which provides for the ability to create real-time reports based on query results and which do not rely on the warehouse or cube.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Team Build (prior to TFS 2015) is a build server application included with Team Foundation Server.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Two components make up Team Build – MSBuild and Windows Workflow Foundation.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] MSBuild is a declarative XML language similar to Apache Ant.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Windows Workflow controls the overall flow of the build process, and Azure DevOps includes many pre-built workflow activities for managing common tasks that are performed during a build.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The build system is extensible with users being able to create their own workflow activities, the ability to inject MSBuild into the process and to execute external processes.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The build process can be configured for various types of builds including scheduled builds, continuous integration, gated check-in and rolling builds.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The build process in Azure DevOps is also part of the traceability mechanism in that Team Build brings together many of the artifacts that are created and stored in Azure DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Assuming developers associate source code with work items on check-in, Team Build has the ability to report on the changes in each build – both source code changes and work item changes as well as test results.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] As bugs and PBIs are resolved and integrated into builds, the work items which track these artifacts are automatically updated to indicate in which build they were successfully integrated.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] Combined with the testing tools, testers then get an integrated view of what code was changed in each build, but also which bugs, PBIs and other work changed from build to build.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] In mid-2013 Microsoft purchased a product called InRelease from InCycle Software.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] InRelease was fully incorporated into Team Foundation Server 2013.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] This capability complemented the automated build and testing processes by allowing a true continuous deployment solution.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The tools were re-branded "Release Management" for TFS 2013.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] The Release Management capabilities give teams the ability to perform a controlled, workflow (provided by Windows Workflow Foundation) driven release to development, test and production environments and provides dashboards for monitoring the progress of one or more releases.
[src:azure-devops/azure-devops-server] This first version of Team Foundation Server was released March 17, 2006.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] In software engineering, **CI/CD** or **CICD** is the combined practices of continuous integration (CI) and continuous delivery (CD) or, less often, continuous deployment.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] They are sometimes referred to collectively as continuous development or continuous software development.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] Producing software in short cycles with high speed and frequency so that reliable software can be released at any time, with a simple and repeatable deployment process when deciding to deploy.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] Automatic rollout of new software functionality.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] When these three processes occur in order, they may be described as a "CI/CD pipeline".
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] CI/CD bridges the gaps between development and operation activities and teams by enforcing automation in building, testing and deployment of applications.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] CI/CD services compile the incremental code changes made by developers, then link and package them into software deliverables.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] Automated tests verify the software functionality, and automated deployment services deliver them to end users.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] The aim is to increase early defect discovery, increase productivity, and provide faster release cycles.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] The process contrasts with traditional methods where a collection of software updates were integrated into one large batch before deploying the newer version.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] of software applications throughout its development life cycle.
[src:azure-devops/ci-cd] The CI/CD practice, or *CI/CD pipeline*, forms the backbone of modern day DevOps operations.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] According to Neal Ford, continuous delivery adopts "Bring the pain forward," tackling tough tasks early, fostering automation and swift issue detection.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery treats the commonplace notion of a *deployment pipeline* as a lean Poka-Yoke: a set of validations through which a piece of software must pass on its way to release.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Code is compiled if necessary and then packaged by a build server every time a change is committed to a source control repository, then tested by a number of different techniques (possibly including manual testing) before it can be marked as releasable.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Developers used to a long cycle time may need to change their mindset when working in a CD environment.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Any code commit may be released to customers at any point.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Patterns such as feature toggles can be very useful for committing code early which is not yet ready for use by end users.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Using NoSQL can eliminate the step of data migrations and schema changes, often manual steps or exceptions to a continuous delivery workflow.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery is enabled through the deployment pipeline.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] The purpose of the deployment pipeline has three components: visibility, feedback, and continually deploy.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] According to Yan Cui, when it comes to serverless environments, ephemeral resources should be kept together and have their own deployment pipeline to achieve a high cohesion.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] However, shared resources that have a long spin-up time and landing zone should have their own separate repository, deployment pipeline and stack.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Continuous delivery takes automation from source control all the way through production.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] There are various tools that help accomplish all or part of this process.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] These tools are part of the deployment pipeline which includes continuous delivery.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] The types of tools that execute various parts of the process include: continuous integration, application release automation, build automation, application lifecycle management.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] To practice continuous delivery effectively, software applications have to meet a set of architecturally significant requirements (ASRs) such as deployability, modifiability, and testability.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] These ASRs require a high priority and cannot be traded off lightly.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Microservices are often used when architecting for continuous delivery.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] The use of Microservices can increase a software system's deployability and modifiability.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] The observed deployability improvements include: deployment independence, shorter deployment time, simpler deployment procedures, and zero downtime deployment.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] The observed modifiability improvements include: shorter cycle time for small incremental functional changes, easier technology selection changes, incremental quality attribute changes, and easier language and library upgrades.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] The original CD book written by Jez Humble and David Farley (2010) popularized the term; however, since its creation the definition has continued to advance and now has a more developed meaning.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Companies today are implementing these continuous delivery principles and best practices.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] The difference in domains, e.g. medical vs. web, is still significant and affects the implementation and usage.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Well-known companies that have this approach include Yahoo!, Amazon, Facebook, Google, Paddy Power and Wells Fargo.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Several benefits of continuous delivery have been reported.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Eight further adoption challenges were raised and elaborated on by Chen.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] These challenges are in the areas of organizational structure, processes, tools, infrastructure, legacy systems, architecting for continuous delivery, continuous testing of non-functional requirements, and test execution optimization.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-delivery] Several strategies to overcome continuous delivery adoption challenges have been reported.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The earliest known work (1989) on continuous integration was the Infuse environment developed by G.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] In 1997, Kent Beck and Ron Jeffries invented extreme programming (XP) while on the Chrysler Comprehensive Compensation System project, including continuous integration.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Beck published about continuous integration in 1998, emphasising the importance of face-to-face communication over technological support.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] In 1999, Beck elaborated more in his first full book on Extreme Programming.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] CruiseControl, one of the first open-source CI tools, was released in 2001.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] In 2010, Timothy Fitz published an article detailing how IMVU's engineering team had built and been using the first practical CD system.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] While his post was originally met with skepticism, it quickly caught on and found widespread adoption as part of the lean software development methodology, also based on IMVU.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The core activities of CI are that developers co-locate code changes in a shared, integration area frequently and that the resulting integrated codebase is verified for correctness.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The first part generally involves merging changes to a common version control branch.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The second part generally involves automated processes including: building, testing and many other processes.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Typically, a server builds from the integration area frequently, i.e. after each commit or periodically, like once a day.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The server may perform quality control checks such as running unit tests and collect software quality metrics via processes such as static analysis and performance testing.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Build automation tools automate building.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend that a single command should have the capability of building the system.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Automation often includes automating the integration, which often includes deployment into a production-like environment.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] In many cases, the build script not only compiles binaries but also generates documentation, website pages, statistics and distribution media (such as Debian DEB, Red Hat RPM or Windows MSI files).
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] CI requires the version control system to support atomic commits; in other words, all of a developer's changes are handled as a single commit.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] When making a code change, a developer creates a branch that is a copy of the current codebase.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] As other changes are committed to the repository, this copy diverges from the latest version.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The longer development continues on a branch without merging to the integration branch, the greater the risk of multiple integration conflicts and failures when the developer branch is eventually merged back.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] When developers submit code to the repository they must first update their code to reflect the changes in the repository since they took their copy.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The more changes the repository contains, the more work developers must do before submitting their own changes.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Eventually, the repository may become so different from the developers' baselines that they enter what is sometimes referred to as "merge hell", or "integration hell", where the time it takes to integrate exceeds the time it took to make their original changes.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI suggest that developers should use test-driven development and to ensure that all unit tests pass locally before committing to the integration branch so that one developer's work does not break another developer's copy.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Incomplete features can be disabled before committing, using feature toggles.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Continuous delivery ensures the software checked in on an integration branch is always in a state that can be deployed to users, and continuous deployment automates the deployment process.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Proponents of CI recommend storing all files and information needed for building in version control (for git a *repository*), and that the system should be buildable from a fresh checkout and not require additional dependencies.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Martin Fowler recommends that all developers commit to the same integration branch.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Developers can reduce the effort of resolving conflicting changes by synchronizing changes with each other frequently, at least daily.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Checking in a week's worth of work risks conflict both in likelihood of occurrence and complexity to resolve.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Relatively small conflicts are significantly easier to resolve than larger ones.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Integrating (committing) changes at least once a day is considered good practice, and more often better.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Building daily, if not more often, is generally recommended.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The system should build commits to the current working version to verify that they integrate correctly.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] A common practice is to use Automated Continuous Integration, although this may be done manually.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Automated continuous integration employs a continuous integration server or daemon to monitor the revision control system for changes, then automatically run the build process.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] When fixing a bug, it is a good practice to push a test case that reproduces the bug.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] This prevents the fix from being reverted and the bug from reappearing, which is known as a regression.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] The build needs to complete rapidly so that if there is a problem with integration, it is quickly identified.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Having a test environment can lead to failures in tested systems when they deploy in the production environment because the production environment may differ from the test environment in a significant way.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] However, building a replica of a production environment is cost-prohibitive.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Instead, the test environment or a separate pre-production environment ("staging") should be built to be a scalable version of the production environment to alleviate costs while maintaining technology stack composition and nuances.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Within these test environments, service virtualisation is commonly used to obtain on-demand access to dependencies (e.g., APIs, third-party applications, services, mainframes, etc.) that are beyond the team's control, still evolving, or too complex to configure in a virtual test lab.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Making builds readily available to stakeholders and testers can reduce the amount of rework necessary when rebuilding a feature that doesn't meet requirements.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Additionally, early testing reduces the chances that defects survive until deployment.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Finding errors earlier can reduce the amount of work necessary to resolve them.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] All programmers should start the day by updating the project from the repository.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] That way, they will all stay up to date.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] It should be easy to find out whether the build breaks and, if so, who made the relevant change and what that change was.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] Most CI systems allow the running of scripts after a build finishes.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] In most situations, it is possible to write a script to deploy the application to a live test server that everyone can look at.
[src:azure-devops/continuous-integration] A further advance in this way of thinking is continuous deployment, which calls for the software to be deployed directly into production, often with additional automation to prevent defects or regressions.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Although debated, DevOps is generally characterized by three key principles: shared ownership, workflow automation, and rapid feedback.
[src:azure-devops/devops] However, the term is used in multiple contexts.
[src:azure-devops/devops] At its most successful, DevOps is a combination of specific practices, culture change, and tools.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Proposals to combine software development methodologies with deployment and operations concepts first appeared in the late 80s and early 90s.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In 2009, the first DevOps Days conference was held in Ghent, Belgium.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The conference was founded by Belgian IT consultant and practitioner Patrick Debois.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The conference has now spread to other countries.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In 2012, the first "State of DevOps" report was published by Alanna Brown at Puppet Labs.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In 2016, the DORA metrics for throughput (deployment frequency, lead time for changes), and stability (mean time to recover, change failure rate) were published in that year's State of DevOps report.
[src:azure-devops/devops] However, the research methodology and metrics were criticized by some experts.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In response to these criticisms, the 2023 State of DevOps report published changes that updated the stability metric "mean time to recover" to "failed deployment recovery time" acknowledging the confusion the previous metric had caused.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The 2024 report restructured the metrics framework by moving failed deployment recovery time from stability to throughput and introducing a new "rework rate" metric measuring the proportion of unplanned deployments made to fix user-visible issues.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In 2025, DORA moved away from sorting teams into performance tiers and instead introduced seven team archetypes that combine delivery metrics with human factors like burnout, friction, and perceived value.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA) has developed a set of metrics which are intended to measure software development efficiency and reliability.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Many of the ideas fundamental to DevOps are similar to other well-known practices, such as Lean and Deming's Plan-Do-Check-Act cycle, The Toyota Way, and the Agile approach of breaking down components and batch sizes.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Contrary to the "top-down" prescriptive approach and rigid framework of ITIL in the 1990s, DevOps is "bottom-up" and flexible, having been created by software engineers for their own needs.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The motivations for what has become modern DevOps and several standard DevOps practices such as automated build and test, continuous integration, and continuous delivery originated in the Agile world, which informally dates to the 1990s and formally to 2001.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Agile development teams using methods such as extreme programming couldn't "satisfy the customer through early and continuous delivery of valuable software" unless they took responsibility for operations and infrastructure for their applications, automating much of that work.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Because Scrum emerged as the dominant Agile framework in the early 2000s and it omitted the engineering practices that were part of many Agile teams, the momentum to automate operations and infrastructure functions splintered from Agile and expanded into what has become modern DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Today, DevOps focuses on deploying methodology-agnostic, developed software.
[src:azure-devops/devops] ArchOps starts from software architecture artifacts instead of source code for operational deployment, as opposed to DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/devops] ArchOps holds that architectural models are first-class entities in software development, deployment, and operations.
[src:azure-devops/devops] CI/CD is as critical to DevOps success as automation.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Additionally, improved collaboration and communication between and within teams helps them achieve faster time to market with reduced risks.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Database DevOps applies DevOps and CI/CD principles directly to database development and operations.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Integrating schema changes, migrations, reference data, and other data-layer updates into the same version-controlled and automated pipelines used for application code enables more reliable deployments.
[src:azure-devops/devops] This approach also enables improved coordination between application and data changes.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Typical database DevOps practices include placing database schema definitions under version control, applying automated tests (such as unit tests or migration validation) to database changes, and deploying those changes through CI/CD pipelines.
[src:azure-devops/devops] These practices reduce what is commonly referred to as "schema drift" between development and production systems and lower the risk of deployment failures.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Mobile DevOps is a methodology that applies DevOps' principles to the development of mobile applications.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Traditional DevOps focuses on streamlining the general software development process, but mobile development has unique challenges that require a tailored approach.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Mobile DevOps is not simply a branch of DevOps specific to mobile app development, but rather an extension and reinterpretation of the DevOps philosophy tailored to mobile's specific requirements.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In 2003, Google developed site reliability engineering (SRE), an approach for releasing new features continuously into large-scale, high-availability systems while maintaining a high-quality end-user experience.
[src:azure-devops/devops] While SRE predates the development of DevOps, they are generally viewed as being related to each other.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Some of the original authors of the discipline consider SRE as an implementation of DevOps.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The Toyota Production System (TPS), inspired lean thinking with its focus on continuous improvement, kaizen, flow, and small batches.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The andon cord principle of creating fast feedback, swarming, and solving problems stems from TPS.
[src:azure-devops/devops] As its name implies, DevSecOps integrates DevOps within security practices.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Contrary to a traditional centralized security team model, each delivery team is empowered to factor the correct security controls into their software delivery.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Teams perform tests and implement security practices earlier in the development lifecycle, hence the term "shift left".
[src:azure-devops/devops] Security is tested in three main areas: static, software composition, and dynamic.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Checking software statically via static application security testing (SAST) is white-box testing with special focus on security.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Depending on the programming language, different tools are needed to do such static code analysis.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The software composition is analyzed, especially libraries, and the version of each component is checked against vulnerability lists published by CERT and other expert groups.
[src:azure-devops/devops] When giving software to clients, library licenses and their match to the license of the software distributed are in focus, especially copyleft licenses.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In dynamic testing, also called black-box testing, software is tested without knowing its inner functions.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In DevSecOps this practice may be referred to as dynamic application security testing (DAST) or penetration testing.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The goal is early detection of defects including cross-site scripting and SQL injection vulnerabilities.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Often, detected defects from static and dynamic testing are triaged and categorized under taxonomies like the Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE), maintained by the Mitre Corporation.
[src:azure-devops/devops] This facilitates the prioritization of security bug fixes and also allows frequently recurring weaknesses to be fixed with recommended mitigations.
[src:azure-devops/devops] As of 2025, CWE maintained its own list of frequently-occurring weaknesses, the CWE Top 25.
[src:azure-devops/devops] In addition, organizations like Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP) maintain lists of industry-wide frequently recurring software weaknesses.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DevSecOps has also been described as a cultural shift involving a holistic approach to producing secure software by integrating security education, security by design, and security automation.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DevOps initiatives can change how a company's operations, developers, and testers collaborate during development and delivery processes.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DevOps attempts to support consistency, reliability, and efficiency within an organization.
[src:azure-devops/devops] This is usually enabled by a shared code repository or version control.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Many organizations use version control to facilitate DevOps automation technologies like virtual machines, containerization (or OS-level virtualization), and CI/CD, with the Git version control system and the GitHub platform referenced as examples.
[src:azure-devops/devops] It takes its name from the popular version control system Git, and the specific state of deployment configuration is also version-controlled.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Configuration changes can be managed using code review practices, and can be rolled back using version-controlling.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Essentially, all of the changes to a code are tracked, bookmarked, and making any updates to the history can be made easier.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DataOps incorporates the Agile methodology to shorten the cycle time of analytics development in alignment with business goals.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DevOps focuses on continuous delivery by leveraging on-demand IT resources and by automating test and deployment of software.
[src:azure-devops/devops] This merging of software *development* and IT *operations* has improved velocity, quality, predictability and scale of software engineering and deployment.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Borrowing methods from DevOps, DataOps seeks to bring these same improvements to data analytics.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DataOps utilizes statistical process control (SPC) to monitor and control the data analytics pipeline.
[src:azure-devops/devops] With SPC in place, the data flowing through an operational system is constantly monitored and verified.
[src:azure-devops/devops] If an anomaly occurs, the data analytics team can be notified with an automated alert.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DataOps is not tied to a particular technology, architecture, tool, language or framework.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The best DataOps tools promote collaboration, orchestration, quality, security, access and ease of use.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DataOps was first introduced by InformationWeek contributing editor Lenny Liebmann in a blog post on the IBM Big Data & Analytics Hub titled "3 reasons why DataOps is essential for big data success" on June 19, 2014.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The term DataOps was later popularized by Andy Palmer of Tamr and Steph Locke.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DataOps is a moniker for "Data Operations." 2017 was a significant year for DataOps, with significant ecosystem development, analyst coverage, increased keyword searches, surveys, publications, and open source projects.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Gartner placed DataOps on the Hype Cycle for Data Management in 2018.
[src:azure-devops/devops] The total world data volume is forecast to grow at a rate of 32% CAGR to 180 Zettabytes by 2025 (Source: IDC).
[src:azure-devops/devops] DataOps seeks to provide the tools, processes, and organizational structures to accommodate this significant increase in data.
[src:azure-devops/devops] Automation streamlines data preboarding, ingestion, and the management of large integrated databases, freeing the data team to develop new analytics in a more efficient and effective way.
[src:azure-devops/devops] DataOps seeks to increase velocity, reliability, and quality of data analytics.
[src:azure-devops/devops] It emphasizes communication, collaboration, integration, automation, measurement and cooperation between data scientists, analysts, data/ETL (extract, transform, load) engineers, information technology (IT), and quality assurance/governance.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:azure-devops/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:azure-devops/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
